{
  "id": "phase-rs_phase_1744",
  "repo_name": "phase-rs/phase",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/phase-rs/phase",
  "base_commit": "8c437c2435e413b8eef4f24a14df919ddec9012d",
  "pr_number": 1744,
  "issue_number": 1740,
  "issue_title": "Combat damage uses stale combat state: dead blockers/attackers still participate (CR 510.1c / 702.19d violated)",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nWhen a creature leaves the battlefield mid-combat (most commonly a blocker dying to **first-strike** combat damage before the regular damage step), it stays recorded in `CombatState.blocker_assignments` / `blocker_to_attacker`. The regular-damage step then reads those stale maps and treats the dead creature as a live combatant. The most visible consequence: a **Double Strike + Trample** attacker assigns lethal damage to a blocker that is already in the graveyard instead of trampling it through, so the defending player takes less damage than the rules require (CR 702.19d).\n\nThis is a genuine bug in fully-wired, supported behavior (first strike, double strike, trample, and multi-block are all implemented and tested) \u2014 not an unimplemented gap.\n\n## Location\n\n`crates/engine/src/game/combat_damage.rs` \u2014 every read of `blocker_assignments` / `blocker_to_attacker` in the damage path:\n- `assign_attacker_damage` (single/none-blocker dispatch),\n- `needs_interactive_assignment` (blocker count),\n- the interactive `DamageSlot` construction in `resolve_combat_damage`,\n- the blocker-damage loop (`distribute_blocker_damage` call).\n\nNone filtered participants by `zone == Battlefield`.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`zones::move_to_zone` removes a dead creature from the battlefield but does **not** prune it from the combat assignment maps (`remove_object_from_combat` is only called on regeneration, phasing, and explicit `RemoveFromCombat` \u2014 not on death-by-SBA). The damage code then reads the raw maps, e.g.:\n\n```rust\nlet blockers = combat\n    .blocker_assignments\n    .get(&attacker_id)\n    .filter(|b| !b.is_empty());   // includes blockers already in the graveyard\n```\n\n`assign_attacker_damage`'s own `None` branch is written to implement CR 702.19d (\"blocked but no blockers remaining \u2192 all damage to the attack target\"), but it can never fire for a dead blocker because the dead blocker is still present in the map, so the single-blocker branch runs and assigns lethal to the corpse.\n\n## CR rules violated (verified against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`)\n\n- **CR 702.19d**: \"If an attacking creature with trample\u2026 is blocked, but there are no creatures blocking it when damage is assigned, its damage is assigned to the defending player and/or planeswalker as though all blocking creatures have been assigned lethal damage.\"\n- **CR 510.1c**: a creature that's no longer on the battlefield assigns/receives no combat damage; a blocked creature with no live blockers assigns no damage (non-trample).\n- **CR 510.1d**: a blocker's damage is divided among the creatures blocking-or-blocked-by it that are still in combat.\n\n## Concrete wrong-vs-correct scenarios\n\n1. **Double Strike + Trample over a dead blocker.** A 5/5 with double strike and trample is blocked by a 2/2.\n   - First-strike step: 2 lethal to the 2/2 + 3 trample to the player; SBAs kill the 2/2 (it goes to the graveyard but stays in `blocker_assignments`).\n   - Regular step (current): the attacker still \"sees\" the dead 2/2, assigns 2 (dropped on apply) + 3 excess \u2192 player takes 3 + 3 = **6**.\n   - Correct (CR 702.19d): the regular step has no blocker \u2192 all 5 trample \u2192 3 + 5 = **8**. The defending player wrongly survives with 2 extra life.\n\n2. **Blocker splitting damage with a dead attacker (CR 510.1d).** A 4/4 blocks two attackers; one dies in the first-strike step. Current code splits the 4/4's damage 2/2 across both, losing 2 to the corpse; correct behavior assigns all 4 to the surviving attacker.\n\n3. **Spurious interactive prompt.** A 2-blocker attacker that loses one blocker in the first-strike step still counts 2 blockers in `needs_interactive_assignment`, prompting for a damage split against a dead blocker.\n\n## Fix (implemented)\n\nAdded a single helper and routed the damage-path reads through it (no change to combat state, triggers, or LKI \u2014 purely a read-time filter):\n\n```rust\nfn live_combatants(state: &GameState, ids: &[ObjectId]) -> Vec<ObjectId> {\n    ids.iter().copied()\n        .filter(|id| state.objects.get(id)\n            .is_some_and(|obj| obj.zone == Zone::Battlefield))\n        .collect()\n}\n```\n\n- `assign_attacker_damage` filters blockers to live ones (so the 702.19d \"no blockers\" path fires).\n- `needs_interactive_assignment` counts only live blockers.\n- The interactive `DamageSlot` list offers only live blockers.\n- The blocker loop splits damage only among live attackers.\n\n## Tests added (`combat_damage.rs`)\n\n- `trample_over_dead_blocker_hits_player_fully` \u2014 trampler whose only blocker is in the graveyard deals all 5 to the player (was 3).\n- `blocker_damage_not_split_with_dead_attacker` \u2014 a 4/4 blocking two attackers (one dead) deals all 4 to the survivor (was split 2/2).\n\nExisting combat-damage tests are unaffected (the filter is a no-op when all participants are on the battlefield).\n\n## Verification\n\n`engine` source change. Per `CLAUDE.md`:\n\n```bash\ncargo fmt --all\n# Tilt up:\n./scripts/tilt-wait.sh --timeout 240 clippy test-engine card-data\n# Tilt down:\ncargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings\ncargo test -p engine -- combat_damage\n```\n\nNote: local compilation was not possible in the authoring environment (no MSVC `link.exe`; GNU toolchain missing `as.exe`/`dlltool`), so the change was verified by `cargo fmt` + manual review; CI runs the full suite.",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-01T10:53:16.000Z",
